#Text=Intrastratal karstification refers to the preferential dissolution of a particular bed or other unit within a sequence of soluble rocks, e.g. a gypsum bed in a dolomite formation.
#Text=Exokarst refers to the suit of karst features developed at the surface.
#Text=Cryptokarst refers to karst forms developed beneath a blanket of permeable sediments such as soil, till, periglacial deposits and residual clays.
#Text=Karst-like landforms produced by processes other than dissolution or corrosion-induced subsidence and collapse are known as pseudokarst.
#Text=Thermokarst is a related term applied to topographic depressions resulting from thawing of ground ice.
#Text=Holokarst is pure karst uninfluenced by other rocks, and is developed on thick limestones extending well below baselevel.
#Text=Concentrated inflows of water from allogenic sources sink underground at swallow holes (also known as swallets, stream-sinks or ponors).
#Text=In contrast, travertine is crystalline, dense calcite that is often well layered, quite lustrous and lacks framing plant content.
#Text=Tufa refers to softer porous material found near cave entrances where rapid deposition is encouraged by evaporation.
#Text=Ideal cave pearls are spheres that range ~0.2 to 10 – 15 mm in diameter.
#Text=Opal (cristobalite) is a very fine-grained silica that occurs as thin interlayers in some calcite and gypsum speleothems.
#Text=The static cave is a simple deep hole with no air drainage out of the bottom ; thus it traps cold, dense air and excludes warmer air.
#Text=Sedimentologists define primary porosity as that created during deposition of the rock (i.e. created first) and secondary porosity as that produced during diagenesis.
#Text=Shaft-like depressions deeply flooded by seawater in low-lying coral islands are known as blue holes.
#Text=Suffosion is the process whereby fines are evacuated through underlying pipes in the karstified bedrock by a combination of physical downwashing and chemical solution.
